    requiresMath: "simple-harmonic-motion",
    sections: [
      { kind: "HERO", content: { scene: "sun", headline: "Energy on the Move", sub: "An oscillator never loses its total energy — it just keeps pouring it back and forth between two forms." } },
      { kind: "CONTEXT", title: "Why this matters", content: { markdown: "Why does a pendulum return to almost exactly the same height on every swing? Why is a mass on a spring moving *fastest* right as it passes through the middle? Both answers come from one of the deepest ideas in physics: **conservation of energy**. Tracking how energy shifts between stored and moving forms tells you the speed at every point of an oscillation without ever solving a differential equation." } },
      { kind: "CONCEPT", title: "The big idea", content: { markdown: "An ideal oscillator (no friction) carries a fixed **total mechanical energy** that continually swaps between two forms:\n\n- **Elastic potential energy** stored in the stretched or compressed spring: $U = \\tfrac12 k x^2$.\n- **Kinetic energy** of the moving mass: $KE = \\tfrac12 m v^2$.\n\nTheir sum is constant:\n\n$$E = \\tfrac12 k x^2 + \\tfrac12 m v^2 = \\text{constant}.$$\n\nAt the **turning points** ($x = \\pm A$) the mass is momentarily at rest, so *all* the energy is potential. Setting $v = 0$ and $x = A$ gives the total:\n\n$$E = \\tfrac12 k A^2.$$\n\nAt the **equilibrium point** ($x = 0$) the spring is relaxed, so *all* the energy is kinetic — and the speed is at its **maximum**. Equating the two extremes, $\\tfrac12 m v_{\\max}^2 = \\tfrac12 k A^2$, gives\n\n$$v_{\\max} = A\\sqrt{\\frac{k}{m}} = A\\,\\omega.$$\n\nSo the energy picture explains the motion: the mass speeds up as it falls toward the middle (PE → KE) and slows as it climbs back out (KE → PE), reaching top speed at the center and a dead stop at the edges." } },
      { kind: "CONCEPT", title: "Derivation: maximum speed", content: { markdown: "Conservation says the energy at the edge equals the energy at the center. At the edge ($x = A$, $v = 0$) all energy is potential:\n\n$$E = \\tfrac12 k A^2.$$\n\nAt the center ($x = 0$) all energy is kinetic:\n\n$$E = \\tfrac12 m v_{\\max}^2.$$\n\nSetting these equal and solving for $v_{\\max}$:\n\n$$\\tfrac12 m v_{\\max}^2 = \\tfrac12 k A^2 \\;\\Rightarrow\\; v_{\\max}^2 = \\frac{k}{m}A^2 \\;\\Rightarrow\\; v_{\\max} = A\\sqrt{\\frac{k}{m}} = A\\omega.$$\n\nA bigger amplitude or a stiffer spring both raise the top speed." } },
      { kind: "WORKED_EXAMPLES", title: "Worked examples", content: { examples: [
        { title: "Total energy", problem: "A spring with $k = 200\\,\\text{N/m}$ oscillates with amplitude $A = 0.1\\,\\text{m}$. Find the total energy.", steps: ["$E = \\tfrac12 k A^2$.", "$E = \\tfrac12 (200)(0.1)^2 = \\tfrac12(200)(0.01) = 1\\,\\text{J}$."], answer: "$E = 1\\,\\text{J}$." },
        { title: "Maximum speed", problem: "A $0.5\\,\\text{kg}$ mass on a $k = 50\\,\\text{N/m}$ spring has amplitude $A = 0.2\\,\\text{m}$. Find $v_{\\max}$.", steps: ["$v_{\\max} = A\\sqrt{k/m} = 0.2\\sqrt{50/0.5}$.", "$\\sqrt{100} = 10$, so $v_{\\max} = 0.2(10) = 2\\,\\text{m/s}$."], answer: "$v_{\\max} = 2\\,\\text{m/s}$." },
        { title: "Where is it fastest?", problem: "At which point of its swing does an oscillating mass move fastest?", steps: ["Speed is maximum where all energy is kinetic.", "That is the equilibrium point, $x = 0$."], answer: "At equilibrium ($x = 0$)." },
      ] } },
      { kind: "CONCEPT_CHECK", title: "Quick check", content: { intro: "Energy is conserved; it is all potential at the edges and all kinetic at the center." } },
      { kind: "PRACTICE", title: "Practice problems", content: { intro: "Use $E = \\tfrac12 k A^2$ and $v_{\\max} = A\\sqrt{k/m}$." } },
      { kind: "DEEPER_DIVE", title: "Deeper dive: why amplitude squared?", content: { markdown: "The total energy $E = \\tfrac12 k A^2$ grows with the **square** of the amplitude — double the swing and you quadruple the energy. This squared dependence is everywhere in oscillations and waves: the loudness of a sound and the brightness of a light both scale with amplitude squared (their *intensity*). It is also why pushing a swing a little harder each cycle adds up so quickly, and why damping — which removes energy at a steady fractional rate — makes the amplitude decay smoothly toward zero." } },
      { kind: "DEEPER_DIVE", title: "Common misconceptions", content: { markdown: "**\"The oscillator is fastest at the turning points.\"** It is *slowest* there — momentarily at rest. It is fastest passing through equilibrium.\n\n**\"Energy is used up over a cycle.\"** In an ideal (frictionless) oscillator total energy is conserved; it only converts between potential and kinetic. Real systems lose energy to friction (damping).\n\n**\"Doubling the amplitude doubles the energy.\"** Energy goes as $A^2$, so doubling the amplitude *quadruples* the energy." } },
      { kind: "SUMMARY", title: "Summary", content: { takeaways: ["Total mechanical energy is conserved and trades between $U = \\tfrac12 kx^2$ and $KE = \\tfrac12 mv^2$.", "Total energy is $E = \\tfrac12 k A^2$ — all potential at the turning points.", "Speed is maximum at equilibrium, where all energy is kinetic.", "Maximum speed is $v_{\\max} = A\\sqrt{k/m} = A\\omega$.", "Energy scales with amplitude squared."], formulas: [{ label: "Total energy", tex: "E = \\tfrac12 k A^2" }, { label: "Energy exchange", tex: "E = \\tfrac12 k x^2 + \\tfrac12 m v^2" }, { label: "Maximum speed", tex: "v_{\\max} = A\\sqrt{\\dfrac{k}{m}}" }] } },
    ],
